<h2>20 Content Ideas That Generate Plumbing Leads</h2>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Social media content ideas for plumbers organized by type and engagement level" src="/images/blog/plumber-social-media-content-ideas.webp" /></p>
<p>Generic "we fixed a leak today" posts do not generate calls. These 20 content types do.</p>
<h3>Trust Builders</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Before/after transformations.</strong> The grosser the "before," the better the engagement. Corroded pipes to new copper. Clogged drains to clear water. These prove your work quality.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer review screenshots.</strong> Screenshot a 5-star Google review. Post it with a thank-you caption. Low effort, high trust signal.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>"How much does it cost?" posts.</strong> Address pricing questions directly. "A basic drain clearing runs $150-300. Here is what affects the price." These get massive engagement because pricing is the number one thing homeowners search for.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Team introduction posts.</strong> Show your technicians by name with a brief bio. Homeowners want to know who is entering their home.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<h3>Education Content</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Quick DIY fixes.</strong> "How to fix a running toilet in 60 seconds." Seems counterintuitive to share free fixes. But homeowners who cannot do it themselves call the person who taught them.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>"Did you know?" plumbing facts.</strong> "The average home wastes 10,000 gallons of water per year from leaks." Educational content positions you as the expert.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Myth-busting posts.</strong> "Lemons sharpen your garbage disposal blades" (false). "Flushable wipes are safe for your pipes" (false). Correcting myths builds authority.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Emergency response tips.</strong> "Your pipe just burst. Here are 3 things to do in the next 5 minutes." Positions you as the first call.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<h3>Visual Content</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Pipe camera footage.</strong> Homeowners have never seen inside their pipes. Camera inspection videos are fascinating and shareable.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Tool explainers.</strong> Show what a hydro-jetter does. Demonstrate a press fitting tool. Most people have never seen professional plumbing equipment.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Day-in-the-life videos.</strong> Morning truck check. First service call. Crawl space work. Lunch break. Afternoon emergency. Humanizes the trade.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Bathroom or kitchen renovation reveals.</strong> Before, during, and after a full plumbing renovation. Tag the homeowner (with permission) for organic reach.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<h3>Seasonal Content</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Winterization checklists.</strong> "5 things to do before the first freeze." Post in September-October for maximum relevance.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Spring plumbing inspection tips.</strong> Sump pump testing, outdoor faucet checks, sprinkler startups. Post in March-April.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Holiday drain warnings.</strong> Thanksgiving is the number one day for drain clogs. Post the week before with prevention tips.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<h3>Community and Recruitment</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Community involvement.</strong> Sponsoring a Little League team. Doing free work for a local nonprofit. Generates shares and goodwill.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Hiring posts.</strong> "Come work with us." Show the trade lifestyle. The plumbing industry has a <a href="https://www.amraandelma.com/plumbing-marketing-statistics/">550,000-worker shortage</a>. Social media doubles as a recruitment tool.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Collaboration posts.</strong> Joint posts with electricians, HVAC techs, or realtors. Cross-pollinates audiences.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<h3>Promotions</h3>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Limited-time offers.</strong> "Book a water heater flush this week and get 15% off." Add urgency with a clear deadline.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>"$15 fix now vs $3,000 repair later" posts.</strong> Visual comparison graphics that drive urgency without being salesy. Show the cost of ignoring small plumbing issues.</p>
</li>
</ol>
